4пёЏвѓЈ Lazy Initialization Singleton

Object is created only when needed.

class Singleton {

    private static Singleton instance;

    private Singleton(){}

    public static Singleton getInstance() {
        if(instance == null) {
            instance = new Singleton();
        }
        return instance;
    }
}

--getInstance() is declared static, so it can be called without creating an object of the class.
--The first call to getInstance() creates the singleton object.
--Subsequent calls return the same instance, ensuring only one object exists.

Advantages

вњ” Object created only when needed
вњ” Saves memory

Problem

вќЊ Not thread-safe

5пёЏвѓЈ Thread Safety Problem

Suppose two threads call getInstance() at the same time

Thread 1

if(instance == null) в†’ true

